#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:4
msgid "Abstract Modules"
msgstr "抽象模組"

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:6
msgid ""
"An abstract module is a special kind of :ref:`module <modules>` which offers "
"points at which its logic can be customized. This takes the form of "
"**abstract methods**, :ref:`internal <structure-functions-internal>` methods "
"decorated with ``@abstract``. These methods can then be overridden to supply "
"the custom logic. Here is an example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:11
msgid ""
"# base_token.vy\n"
"# This is the abstract module\n"
"\n"
"balances: public(HashMap[address, uint256])\n"
"\n"
"# Abstract method is declared here\n"
"@abstract\n"
"def _before_transfer(sender: address, recipient: address, amount: uint256):\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"@external\n"
"def transfer(recipient: address, amount: uint256):\n"
"    # and used here\n"
"    self._before_transfer(msg.sender, recipient, amount)\n"
"    self.balances[msg.sender] -= amount\n"
"    self.balances[recipient] += amount"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:30
msgid ""
"The ``base_token`` module defines a transfer hook, ``_before_transfer()``, "
"as an abstract method. It is called during every transfer, but has no "
"implementation — that is left to whoever initializes this module. This lets "
"this module focus on *where* custom logic runs, while the overriding module "
"decides *what* it does."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:32
msgid ""
"To supply an implementation, a module imports and ``initializes`` the "
"abstract module, then provides an ``@override`` for each abstract method:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:34
msgid ""
"# pausable_token.vy\n"
"\n"
"import base_token\n"
"\n"
"initializes: base_token\n"
"\n"
"exports: base_token.transfer\n"
"\n"
"paused: public(bool)\n"
"\n"
"@override(base_token)\n"
"def _before_transfer(sender: address, recipient: address, amount: uint256):\n"
"    assert not self.paused, \"transfers are paused\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:51
msgid ""
"Now every call to ``base_token.transfer()`` will check the pause flag before "
"moving tokens. The override is resolved at compile time — there is no "
"runtime dispatch or inheritance involved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:53
msgid ""
"As you can see in the example above, what makes a module \"abstract\" is "
"only the presence of abstract methods. Furthermore, that is the only "
"difference, everything that can be done in a concrete (i.e. non-abstract) "
"module can also be done in an abstract module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:57
msgid "Abstract methods"
msgstr "抽象方法"

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:59
msgid ""
"An abstract method is an :ref:`internal method <structure-functions-"
"internal>` decorated with ``@abstract``. Its body must consist of an "
"Ellipsis literal (``...``) potentially preceded by a docstring and comments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:62
msgid ""
"@abstract\n"
"def an_abstract_method(x: uint256) -> uint256:\n"
"    \"\"\"This is a docstring\"\"\"\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:69
msgid ""
"There are no other restrictions on abstract methods, they can have any "
"signature, can take any decorator (provided they are valid on internal "
"methods), and be called like concrete methods:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:71
msgid ""
"@pure\n"
"@abstract\n"
"def name() -> String[10]:\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"@payable\n"
"@nonreentrant\n"
"@abstract\n"
"def foo(bar: DynArray[Bytes[20], 10]) -> DynArray[String[15], 38]:\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"def concrete_calls():\n"
"    _name: String[10] = self.name()\n"
"    complex_expression: String[15] = self.foo([]).pop()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:89
msgid "Overriding an abstract module"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:91
msgid ""
"As abstract modules are by essence incomplete, it is necessary for another "
"module to complete them, by providing implementations for its abstract "
"methods:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:93
msgid ""
"import base_token\n"
"\n"
"initializes: base_token\n"
"\n"
"@override(base_token)\n"
"def _before_transfer(sender: address, recipient: address, amount: uint256):\n"
"    assert not self.paused, \"transfers are paused\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:103
msgid "For module M1 to override module M2:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:105
msgid "M1 must :ref:`initialize <initializing-module>` M2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:106
msgid ""
"M1 must override each abstract method of M2, see :ref:`Overriding abstract "
"methods <overriding-abstract-methods>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:109
msgid ""
"So there is no choice to be made about which override to choose, abstract "
"modules can only be overridden once. This is guaranteed by the "
"initialization system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:114
msgid "Overriding abstract methods"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:116
msgid ""
"To override abstract method ``_before_transfer`` of module ``base_token``, "
"the overriding module must define an internal method ``_before_transfer`` "
"with an ``@override(my_abstract_module)`` decorator:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:118
msgid ""
"@override(base_token)\n"
"def _before_transfer(sender: address, recipient: address, amount: uint256):\n"
"    assert not self.paused, \"transfers are paused\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:124
msgid ""
"Since any call to ``base_token._before_transfer`` will be replaced at "
"compile-time to a call to the overriding ``_before_transfer``, it is "
"necessary that any call to the former is a valid call to the latter:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:126
msgid ""
"# abstract_m.vy\n"
"@pure\n"
"@abstract\n"
"def compute(x: uint256) -> uint256:\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:134
msgid ""
"import abstract_m\n"
"initializes: abstract_m\n"
"\n"
"# Valid: signature matches exactly\n"
"@pure\n"
"@override(abstract_m)\n"
"def compute(x: uint256) -> uint256:\n"
"    return x + 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:145
msgid ""
"import abstract_m\n"
"initializes: abstract_m\n"
"\n"
"# Invalid: parameter and return type don't match the ones in abstract_m."
"compute\n"
"@pure\n"
"@override(abstract_m)\n"
"def compute(x: uint8) -> uint8:\n"
"    return x + 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:156
msgid ""
"import abstract_m\n"
"initializes: abstract_m\n"
"\n"
"# Invalid: parameter name doesn't match\n"
"@pure\n"
"@override(abstract_m)\n"
"def compute(y: uint256) -> uint256:\n"
"    return y + 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:167
msgid ""
"import abstract_m\n"
"initializes: abstract_m\n"
"\n"
"# Invalid: Has looser mutability: nonpayable vs the original which is pure\n"
"@nonpayable\n"
"@override(abstract_m)\n"
"def compute(y: uint256) -> uint256:\n"
"    return y + 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:178
msgid "A good heuristic is the following; the override must have:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:180
msgid ""
"The same parameters as the abstract method: same name, same type, and same "
"default value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:181
msgid "The same return type as the abstract method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:182
msgid ""
"The same decorators as the abstract method, except ``@override`` and "
"``@abstract``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:184
msgid ""
"Following the rules above will always result in a valid override. However "
"these might prove too restrictive in your use-case, for this reason the "
"actual rules are more flexible:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:187
msgid ""
"Each parameter of the abstract method must appear in the override at the "
"same position, with the same name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:188
msgid ""
"If the abstract method defines a default argument for a parameter, the value "
"of the default argument must match in the override. Any value matches an "
"ellipsis (``...``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:189
msgid ""
"The override may add extra parameters to the right, as long as they have "
"default values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:190
msgid ""
"The override may add a default value to a parameter that was mandatory in "
"the abstract method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:191
msgid ""
"Each parameter type in the override must be a super-type of the "
"corresponding parameter type in the abstract method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:192
msgid ""
"The return type of the override must be a sub-type of the abstract method's "
"return type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:193
msgid ""
"The override's :ref:`mutability <function-mutability>` must be the same (or "
"stricter) than the abstract's."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:194
msgid ""
"The override's :ref:`reentrancy <reentrancy>` must match exactly the one of "
"the abstract method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:198
msgid "Calling abstract methods"
msgstr "呼叫抽象方法"

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:200
msgid ""
"Abstract methods are called in the same way concrete methods are. "
"Additionally, calling the abstract methods of another module requires :ref:"
"`using <uses-statement>` it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:203
msgid ""
"# base_token.vy\n"
"\n"
"@abstract\n"
"def _before_transfer(sender: address, recipient: address, amount: uint256):\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"@external\n"
"def transfer(recipient: address, amount: uint256):\n"
"    # call to abstract method in same module\n"
"    self._before_transfer(msg.sender, recipient, amount)\n"
"    self.balances[msg.sender] -= amount\n"
"    self.balances[recipient] += amount"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:218
msgid ""
"import base_token\n"
"\n"
"# required by the call below\n"
"uses: base_token\n"
"\n"
"def simulate_transfer(sender: address, recipient: address, amount: "
"uint256):\n"
"    # call to abstract method in different module\n"
"    base_token._before_transfer(sender, recipient, amount)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:229
msgid ""
"All calls to abstract methods are resolved at compile time to the concrete "
"override: there is no runtime dispatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:231
msgid ""
"When a module overrides an abstract method, the compiler requires callers to "
"use the most concrete path available. In particular, if ``self."
"_before_transfer`` overrides ``base_token._before_transfer``, any call "
"within that module must go through ``self``, not through ``base_token``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:234
msgid ""
"import base_token\n"
"\n"
"initializes: base_token\n"
"\n"
"@override(base_token)\n"
"def _before_transfer(sender: address, recipient: address, amount: uint256):\n"
"    assert not self.paused, \"transfers are paused\"\n"
"\n"
"def foo():\n"
"    # Valid: uses the override directly\n"
"    self._before_transfer(msg.sender, msg.sender, 0)\n"
"\n"
"    # Invalid: base_token._before_transfer is overridden by\n"
"    # self._before_transfer, call that instead.\n"
"    base_token._before_transfer(msg.sender, msg.sender, 0)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:254
msgid "Advanced Uses"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:256
msgid ""
"In this section we will explain consequences of the above specification "
"which might not jump to mind, and are useful in advanced contexts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:259
msgid "Abstract overriding modules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:261
msgid ""
"An overriding module can itself be abstract. In other words, ``@abstract`` "
"and ``@override`` can co-exist in the same module (and even :ref:`on the "
"same method <deferring_overriding>`):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:264
msgid ""
"# checked_token.vy\n"
"\n"
"import base_token\n"
"\n"
"initializes: base_token\n"
"\n"
"@override(base_token)\n"
"def _before_transfer(sender: address, recipient: address, amount: uint256):\n"
"    assert self.check_address(sender), \"Invalid sender\"\n"
"    assert self.check_address(recipient), \"Invalid recipient\"\n"
"    assert self.check_cap(amount), \"Invalid amount\"\n"
"\n"
"@abstract\n"
"def check_cap(amount: uint256) -> bool:\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"@abstract\n"
"def check_address(addr: address) -> bool:\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:286
msgid ""
"Here ``checked_token.vy`` provides a concrete ``_before_transfer`` for "
"``base_token``, but it is itself an abstract module because it introduces "
"``check_cap`` and ``check_address``. A final module completes the chain by "
"overriding those:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:288
msgid ""
"# my_token.vy\n"
"import checked_token\n"
"\n"
"initializes: checked_token\n"
"\n"
"MAX_AMOUNT: constant(uint256) = 10**24\n"
"total_supply: uint256\n"
"\n"
"@override(checked_token)\n"
"def check_cap(amount: uint256) -> bool:\n"
"    return 0 < amount and amount <= MAX_AMOUNT\n"
"\n"
"@override(checked_token)\n"
"def check_address(addr: address) -> bool:\n"
"    return addr != empty(address)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:307
msgid "Overriding multiple modules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:309
msgid ""
"A single module can initialize more than one abstract module, providing "
"overrides for each independently. This is how you compose unrelated "
"concerns, for instance combining transfer validation from one module with "
"fee configuration from another."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:312
msgid ""
"Using ``base_token`` from the :ref:`earlier example <abstract-modules>`, "
"consider a second abstract module that manages access control:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:314
msgid ""
"# access_control.vy\n"
"\n"
"@abstract\n"
"def _is_allowed(user: address) -> bool:\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"def check_allowed(user: address):\n"
"    assert self._is_allowed(user), \"access denied\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:325
msgid ""
"A contract can initialize both modules and override each abstract method:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:327
msgid ""
"# my_token.vy\n"
"\n"
"import base_token\n"
"import access_control\n"
"\n"
"initializes: base_token\n"
"initializes: access_control\n"
"\n"
"exports: base_token.transfer\n"
"\n"
"allowed: HashMap[address, bool]\n"
"\n"
"@override(access_control)\n"
"def _is_allowed(user: address) -> bool:\n"
"    return self.allowed[user]\n"
"\n"
"@override(base_token)\n"
"def _before_transfer(sender: address, recipient: address, amount: uint256):\n"
"    access_control.check_allowed(sender)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:349
msgid ""
"The overriding module weaves both concerns together: ``_before_transfer`` "
"delegates to the access control module to gate who can send tokens."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:352
msgid "Overriding multiple abstract methods"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:354
msgid ""
"When a module overrides multiple others, it might happen that the abstract "
"modules share a method name. To handle this case, it is possible for a "
"single method to override multiple, by adding multiple ``@override`` "
"decorators. Note however that the method must be a :ref:`valid override "
"<overriding-abstract-methods>` for every abstract method:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:358
msgid ""
"# minter.vy\n"
"\n"
"import my_roles\n"
"\n"
"@abstract\n"
"def get_role(user: address) -> my_roles.ROLE:\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:368
msgid ""
"# authentication_provider.vy\n"
"\n"
"import my_roles\n"
"\n"
"@abstract\n"
"def get_role(user: address, default_role: my_roles.ROLE) -> my_roles.ROLE:\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:378
msgid ""
"import minter\n"
"import authentication_provider\n"
"import my_roles\n"
"initializes: minter\n"
"initializes: authentication_provider\n"
"\n"
"roles: HashMap[address, my_roles.ROLE]\n"
"\n"
"# By having `default_role` as an optional parameter, it's a valid override "
"of both\n"
"# `minter.get_role` which does not have that parameter, and\n"
"# `authentication_provider.get_role` which has it as a mandatory parameter\n"
"\n"
"@override(minter)\n"
"@override(authentication_provider)\n"
"def get_role(user: address, default_role: my_roles.ROLE = empty(my_roles."
"ROLE)) -> my_roles.ROLE:\n"
"    role: my_roles.ROLE = self.roles[user]\n"
"    if role == empty(my_roles.ROLE):\n"
"        return default_role\n"
"    return role"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:404
msgid "Deferring overriding"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:406
msgid ""
"In some cases a module might not want to override every method of another, "
"if such is the case, ``@abstract`` and ``@override`` can be combined to "
"defer providing an implementation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:408
msgid ""
"# base.vy\n"
"\n"
"@abstract\n"
"def method_a() -> uint256:\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"@abstract\n"
"def method_b() -> uint256:\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:420
msgid ""
"# middle.vy\n"
"import base\n"
"\n"
"initializes: base\n"
"\n"
"# Concrete override\n"
"@override(base)\n"
"def method_a() -> uint256:\n"
"    return 0\n"
"\n"
"# Delegates\n"
"@abstract\n"
"@override(base)\n"
"def method_b() -> uint256:\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:438
msgid ""
"# top.vy\n"
"import middle\n"
"\n"
"initializes: middle\n"
"\n"
"@override(middle)\n"
"def method_b() -> uint256:\n"
"    return 42"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:449
msgid ""
"Any call to ``base.method_b`` resolves to a call to the concrete "
"implementation: ``top.method_b``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:452
msgid "Default Implementation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:454
msgid ""
"It's sometimes desirable to provide a default implementation for an abstract "
"method, this can be done by defining a separate method which holds this "
"logic:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:456
msgid ""
"# base_token.vy\n"
"\n"
"@abstract\n"
"def _before_transfer(sender: address, recipient: address, amount: uint256):\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"def _before_transfer_default(sender: address, recipient: address, amount: "
"uint256):\n"
"    assert sender != empty(address), \"transfer from zero address\"\n"
"    assert recipient != empty(address), \"transfer to zero address\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:468
msgid "This allows accepting the default implementation downstream as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:470
msgid ""
"# simple_token.vy\n"
"\n"
"import base_token\n"
"\n"
"initializes: base_token\n"
"\n"
"@override(base_token)\n"
"def _before_transfer(sender: address, recipient: address, amount: uint256):\n"
"    base_token._before_transfer_default(sender, recipient, amount)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:482
msgid ""
"And even allows using the default implementation while adding extra logic:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:484
msgid ""
"# pausable_token.vy\n"
"\n"
"import base_token\n"
"\n"
"initializes: base_token\n"
"\n"
"paused: public(bool)\n"
"\n"
"@override(base_token)\n"
"def _before_transfer(sender: address, recipient: address, amount: uint256):\n"
"\n"
"    # Use default check\n"
"    base_token._before_transfer_default(sender, recipient, amount)\n"
"\n"
"    # Add custom logic\n"
"    assert not self.paused, \"transfers are paused\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:503
msgid "Recommendations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:505
msgid ""
"The default implementation should have the same name as the abstract method "
"followed by ``_default``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../abstract-modules.rst:506
msgid ""
"The default implementation should not be called anywhere (except in the "
"override), as this defeats the purpose of making the method abstract in the "
"first place."
msgstr ""
